<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41072e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41072e">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41072e"> 72(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">C</font> keeps her / letters <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n41072e"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">I believe him <font color="green">[Bywaters]</font> to have been a virile degenerate, quite capable of blackmail; and that one reason why he so carefully <mark>kept all these letters</mark>, while she destroyed his, was that if and when he wanted to get rid of her he would have something to hold over her in the way of threat. <small> Filson Young, <a name="FYTF" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FYTF"><cite title="source">Trial of Frederick Bywaters and Edith Thompson</cite></a> (1923) xxviii</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Filson Young seems to be overcompensating here for the very unfair treatment of Mrs Thompson by public opinion at the time. This is certainly a most unusual and scarcely justifiable view of Bywaters, not shared by any other commentator on the case, as far as I am aware. </mm> </dd></dl>
